WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:06.804
Bronchiectasis is a chronic structural
lung disease where the airways become permanently dilated and

2
00:00:06.804 --> 00:00:08.864
damaged, leading to impaired mucus
clearance,

3
00:00:09.385 --> 00:00:12.125
recurrent infections, and progressive lung
dysfunction.

4
00:00:12.845 --> 00:00:16.325
For respiratory therapists, the key is
understanding the cycle.

5
00:00:17.305 --> 00:00:18.545
Infection causes inflammation.

6
00:00:19.405 --> 00:00:23.225
Inflammation damages the airway, and that
damage leads to mucus

7
00:00:23.225 --> 00:00:24.784
buildup and more infection.

8
00:00:25.004 --> 00:00:29.305
In bronchiectasis, the normal airway
defense system breaks down.

9
00:00:29.825 --> 00:00:33.564
Thick secretions accumulate, ciliary
function is impaired,

10
00:00:34.044 --> 00:00:36.685
and bacteria colonize the lungs.

11
00:00:37.005 --> 00:00:40.465
Over time, this creates a vicious cycle of
inflammation and

12
00:00:40.465 --> 00:00:42.944
infection that worsens airway damage.

13
00:00:44.244 --> 00:00:47.924
Unlike asthma or COPD, this damage is
irreversible.

14
00:00:49.025 --> 00:00:52.424
Clinically, patients often present with
chronic productive cough,

15
00:00:53.205 --> 00:00:55.724
large amounts of sputum, frequent
infections,

16
00:00:56.005 --> 00:00:57.705
and sometimes hemoptysis.

17
00:00:58.764 --> 00:01:01.244
Breath sounds may include crackles,
ronchi,

18
00:01:01.444 --> 00:01:02.084
or wheezing.

19
00:01:02.904 --> 00:01:07.644
A major red flag is increasing sputum
volume, worsening dyspnea,

20
00:01:08.105 --> 00:01:10.845
or signs of infection like fever and
fatigue.

21
00:01:12.004 --> 00:01:15.925
Diagnosis is confirmed with a
high-resolution CT scan, which

22
00:01:15.925 --> 00:01:18.004
shows dilated, thickened airways.

23
00:01:18.885 --> 00:01:22.525
Pulmonary function tests often show an
obstructive pattern, but the

24
00:01:22.525 --> 00:01:25.785
key distinction is the structural damage
seen on imaging.

25
00:01:27.184 --> 00:01:29.184
Management focuses heavily on airway
clearance.

26
00:01:29.944 --> 00:01:33.025
This is one of the most important roles
for the respiratory therapist.

27
00:01:34.084 --> 00:01:37.525
Techniques include chest physiotherapy,
oscillatory devices,

28
00:01:38.165 --> 00:01:42.245
and positive expiratory pressure therapy
to mobilize secretions.

29
00:01:43.004 --> 00:01:47.084
Bronchodilators may be used to improve
airflow, and antibiotics are

30
00:01:47.084 --> 00:01:51.425
critical during exacerbations or for
chronic suppression in some patients.

31
00:01:52.205 --> 00:01:56.125
Hydration and mucolytics can also help
thin secretions, making them

32
00:01:56.125 --> 00:01:56.964
easier to clear.

33
00:01:57.925 --> 00:02:02.025
In severe cases, patients may require
oxygen therapy or advanced

34
00:02:02.025 --> 00:02:02.605
interventions.

35
00:02:03.165 --> 00:02:08.184
From a board prep perspective, always
think chronic productive cough,

36
00:02:08.764 --> 00:02:14.225
recurrent infections, and airway dilation
on CT equals bronchiectasis.

37
00:02:14.985 --> 00:02:19.225
And from an RT standpoint, remember that
secretion management is

38
00:02:19.225 --> 00:02:19.925
not optional.

39
00:02:20.585 --> 00:02:22.145
It is the cornerstone of care.

40
00:02:23.145 --> 00:02:26.645
Ultimately, your goal is to break the
infection inflammation cycle,

41
00:02:27.824 --> 00:02:31.065
improve airway clearance, and monitor for
worsening disease.

42
00:02:31.244 --> 00:02:35.384
If you can recognize the pattern and
intervene early, you

43
00:02:35.384 --> 00:02:37.964
can significantly improve patient
outcomes.

